{{Wikidatabox}} [[File:Katsurarikyu01.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Garden of Katsura Imperial Villa]]
'''Kaiyū-shiki Teien''' (回遊式庭園) is a style of {{ill|Japanese garden|ja|日本庭園|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese garden|qq=}} designed for strolling and viewing various landscapes within the garden. While strolling-style gardens exist outside Japan, the term "kaiyū-shiki teien" typically refers to Japanese gardens specifically.
== Overview ==
Kaiyū-shiki teien became prominent during the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi period|qq=}} in {{ill|Zen Buddhism|ja|禅宗|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zen Buddhism|qq=}} temples and were extensively developed by {{ill|daimyō|ja|大名|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/daimyō|qq=}} during the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}. This style is considered a culmination of Japanese garden design.
The most common type is the '''{{ill|Pond Strolling Garden|ja|池泉庭園|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Pond Strolling Garden|qq=}}''' (池泉回遊式庭園), which features a central pond surrounded by paths. These paths allow visitors to enjoy views of {{ill|artificial hills|ja|築山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/artificial hills|qq=}}, small islands in the pond, bridges, and {{ill|ornamental stones|ja|庭石|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ornamental stones|qq=}} representing scenic locations. Along the pathways, structures such as {{ill|teahouses|ja|茶室|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/teahouses|qq=}} and {{ill|azumaya|ja|四阿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/azumaya|qq=}} were built to serve as rest stops and observation points.
== Representative Kaiyū-shiki Teien ==
